{"title_page": "Edward Douglas Fawcett", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n'''Edward Douglas Fawcett''' (11 April 1866 \u2013 14 April 1960) was an English mountaineer, philosopher and novelist.\n\n==Life==\nEdward Douglas Fawcett was born in [[Hove]], Sussex on 11 April 1866.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|title=Contemporary British Philosophy: Personal Statements|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6mQj21I8z4C&pg=PA83|year=1924|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-29555-0|page=84}}</ref> He was the elder son of [[Edward Fawcett]], an [[equerry]] to the [[Prince of Wales]], (King Edward VII)<ref name=\"Times\">\"Mr. Douglas Fawcett.\" Times, 18 April 1960, p. 10</ref> and the older brother of explorer [[Percy Fawcett]]. He was educated at [[Newton Abbot College]] in Devon and was a Queen's Scholar at [[Westminster School]] from 1880.<ref name=\"Times\"/>\n\nFawcett converted to [[Buddhism]], having taken the pansil (the [[Laity|lay]] follower vow to the [[Five Precepts]]) while with [[Henry Steel Olcott]] in [[Ceylon]] (modern Sri Lanka) in January 1890.<ref>{{cite book |last=Grann |first=David |year=2010 |title=The Lost City of Z |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=London |page=41}}</ref><ref name=\"Lucifer66\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last= de Harlez |first=C. |title=The Buddhist Propaganda in Christian Countries |journal=The Dublin Review |series=Third Series |date=July 1890 |volume=XXIV |issue=1 |page=56 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uBEJAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA56 |accessdate=10 July 2018 |publisher=Burns & Oates Limited |location=London}}</ref> He was an associate of Russian occultist [[Helena Blavatsky]], leading theoretician of the esoteric religious movement [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophy]].  He assisted her in her writing and in compiling quotations from scientific works for ''[[The Secret Doctrine]]''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wachtmeiste |first1=Constance |title=Reminiscences of H. P. Blavatsky and 'The Secret Doctrine' |date=1893 |publisher=Theosophical Publishing Society |location=London |page=94 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u-UYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA94 |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> and particularly the parts of second volume on the topic of evolutionary hypotheses.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wachtmeiste |first1=Constance |title=Reminiscences of H. P. Blavatsky and 'The Secret Doctrine' |date=1893 |publisher=Theosophical Publishing Society |location=London |page=99 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u-UYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA99 |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> Fawcett joined the editorial staff of [[The Theosophist]], the monthly journal of the [[Theosophical Society]]<ref name=\"Lucifer161\">{{cite journal |journal=Lucifer |title=Theosophical Activities |date=15 April 1890 |volume=VI |issue=32 |page=161 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5yvYAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA161 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref> and wrote correspondence for the magazine ''[[Lucifer (magazine)|Lucifer]]''.<ref name=\"Lucifer66\">{{cite journal |journal=Lucifer |last=Fawcett |first=E. Douglass |title=Theosophical Activities \u2013 From Our Far East Station |date=15 March 1890 |volume=VI |issue=31 |pages=66\u201368|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5yvYAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA66 |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs a science fiction author, Fawcett published his first fantasy novel ''[[Hartmann the Anarchist]]'' in 1893.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Menville |first1=Douglas |title=Classics of Science Fiction and Fantasy |journal=Forgotten Fantasy |date=June 1971 |issue=5 |pages=7\u201310 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fYsiuGeM8DUC&pg=PA7 |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> He published two adventure novels in the 1890s.  His 1894 novel ''Swallowed by an Earthquake'' drew favourable comparisons in London to the works of Jules Verne.<ref>{{cite journal |title=A Weekly Review of Literature, Science, and Art |journal=The Academy |date=12 January 1895 |volume=XLVI |page=491 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1QQ9AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA491 |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Bookseller |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WPgiAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA53 |accessdate=5 July 2018 |issue=CCCCXLVI |date=9 January 1895 |location=London |pages=53}}</ref>\n\nHe also authored multiple books on philosophy, including ''The Riddle of the Universe'' in 1893 on the [[metaphysical]] concept of [[Monadology]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carus |first1=Paul |title=The Key to the Riddle of the Universe. A Disquisition on Mr. Edward Douglas Fawcett's Philosophy |journal=The Monist |date=April 1895 |volume=5 |issue=3 |pages=408\u2013411 |jstor=27897251 }}</ref> In the preface to his 1909 essay, ''The Individual and Reality'', Fawcett concedes to having abandoned Monadology in favour of the metaphysical philosophies of [[Idealism]]<ref name=\"Individual\"/>\n\nFawcett married his cousin in M. B. V. Jackson in 1896.<ref name=\"auto\"/> and they lived principally in Switzerland for many years.<ref>{{cite book|author=Rudolf Metz|title=A Hundred Years of British Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=erS3AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA433|date=3 June 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-85322-0|page=433}}</ref>\n\nFawcett devoted his life to mountaineering and philosophy.<ref name=\"Times\"/> During this time, his philosophy centered around the idea that imagination was the fundamental reality of the universe.<ref name=\"auto1\">Who Was Who</ref> Fawcett and his wife became the first people to ascend the [[Mer de Glace]] by automobile in 1909.<ref>\"Montanvert Climbed by Auto for First Time.\" New York Herald [European Edition], 8 August 1909, p. 6.</ref>\n\nFawcett returned to England and in 1947, he married his second wife, Vera Dick-Cunyngham, widow of George Dick-Cunyngham.  Fawcett died in London on 14 April 1960.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Literary Works==\n(1891) ''The Power Behind the Universe''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Edward Douglass |title=The Power Behind the Universe |date=1891 |publisher=Scottish Press |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=krz9MgEACAAJ |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n(1893) ''[[Hartmann the Anarchist]]'' or the Doom of the Great City<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Edward Douglas |title=Hartmann the Anarchist or the Doom of the Great City |date=1893 |publisher=Edward Arnold |location=London |url=https://archive.org/details/hartmannanarchi00fawcgoog|quote=hartmann the anarchist. }}</ref> a science fiction adventure where the title character Hartmann engages in airship warfare and depicts an aerial bombardment of the city of London. Illustrations were by [[Fred T. Jane]].\n\n(1893) ''The Riddle of the Universe: Being an Attempt to Determine the First Principles of Metaphysic''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Edward Douglass |title=The Riddle of the Universe: Being an Attempt to Determine the First Principles of Metaphysic |date=1893 |publisher=Edward Arnold |location=London |url=https://archive.org/details/riddleuniverseb00fawcgoog |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n(1894) ''Swallowed by an Earthquake''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f36qPAAACAAJ|title=Swallowed by an Earthquake|last=Fawcett|first=Edward Douglas|publisher=Edward Around|year=1894|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> a [[subterranean fiction]] adventure about the discovery of an underground world of dinosaurs and cannibals.\n\n(1895) ''The Secret Life of the Desert'' an adventure novel following the exploits of archaeologist Arthur Mannors in Arabia.\n\n(1909) ''The Individual and Reality: An Essay Touching the First Principles of Metaphysics''<ref name=\"Individual\">{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Edward Douglass |title=The Individual and Reality: An Essay Touching the First Principles of Metaphysics |date=1909 |publisher=Longmans, Green, and Co. |url=https://archive.org/details/individualandre00fawcgoog |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n(1916) ''The World as Imagination''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Edward Douglas |title=The World as Imagination |date=1916 |publisher=MacMillan and Co, Ltd |location=London |url=https://archive.org/details/worldasimaginat00fawcgoog|quote=edward fawcett. }}</ref>\n\n(1921) ''Divine Imagining: An Essay on the First Principles of Philosophy''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Divine_Imagining.html?id=2WSToAEACAAJ&source=kp_cover|title=Divine Imagining: An Essay on the First Principles of Philosophy|last=Fawcett|first=Edward Douglass|publisher=|year=1921|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n(1936) ''From Heston to the High Alps: A Chat About Joy-Flying''\n<ref>{{cite web |title=From Heston to the High Alps: A Chat About Joy-Flying|url=https://stellabooks.com/books/douglas-fawcett/from-heston-to-the-high-alps-a-chat-about-joy-flying/1812969 |website=Stella & Rose's Books: Specialists in Rare & Collectable Books |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://theosophy.wiki/en/Edward_Douglas_Fawcett Edward Douglas Fawcett] on Theosophy Wiki\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120403012650/http://www.keverelchess.com/e-douglas-fawcett-1866-1960/ E. Douglas Fawcett (1866\u20131960)] on Keverel Chess\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fawcett, Edward Douglas}}\n[[Category:English Buddhists]]\n[[Category:English Theosophists]]\n[[Category:English science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English mountain climbers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hove]]\n[[Category:English philosophers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n'''Edward Douglas Fawcett''' (11 April 1866 \u2013 14 April 1960) was an English mountaineer, philosopher and novelist.\n\n==Life==\nEdward Douglas Fawcett was born in [[Hove]], Sussex on 11 April 1866.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|title=Contemporary British Philosophy: Personal Statements|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6mQj21I8z4C&pg=PA83|year=1924|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-29555-0|page=84}}</ref> He was the elder son of [[Edward Fawcett]], an [[equerry]] to the [[Prince of Wales]], (King Edward VII)<ref name=\"Times\">\"Mr. Douglas Fawcett.\" Times, 18 April 1960, p. 10</ref> and the older brother of explorer [[Percy Fawcett]]. He was educated at [[Newton Abbot College]] in Devon and was a Queen's Scholar at [[Westminster School]] from 1880.<ref name=\"Times\"/>\n\nFawcett converted to [[Buddhism]], having taken the pansil (the [[Laity|lay]] follower vow to the [[Five Precepts]]) while with [[Henry Steel Olcott]] in [[Ceylon]] (modern Sri Lanka) in January 1890.<ref>{{cite book |last=Grann |first=David |year=2010 |title=The Lost City of Z |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=London |page=41}}</ref><ref name=\"Lucifer66\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last= de Harlez |first=C. |title=The Buddhist Propaganda in Christian Countries |journal=The Dublin Review |series=Third Series |date=July 1890 |volume=XXIV |issue=1 |page=56 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uBEJAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA56 |accessdate=10 July 2018 |publisher=Burns & Oates Limited |location=London}}</ref> He was an associate of Russian occultist [[Helena Blavatsky]], leading theoretician of the esoteric religious movement [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophy]].  He assisted her in her writing and in compiling quotations from scientific works for the''[[The Secret Doctrine]]''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wachtmeiste |first1=Constance |title=Reminiscences of H. P. Blavatsky and 'The Secret Doctrine' |date=1893 |publisher=Theosophical Publishing Society |location=London |page=94 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u-UYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA94 |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> and particularly the parts of second volume on the topic of evolutionary hypotheses.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wachtmeiste |first1=Constance |title=Reminiscences of H. P. Blavatsky and 'The Secret