rg/details/hartmannanarchi00fawcgoog|quote=hartmann the anarchist. }}</ref> a science fiction adventure where the title character Hartmann engages in airship warfare and depicts an aerial bombardment of the city of London. Illustrations were by [[Fred T. Jane]].\n\n(1893) ''The Riddle of the Universe: Being an Attempt to Determine the First Principles of Metaphysic''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Edward Douglass |title=The Riddle of the Universe: Being an Attempt to Determine the First Principles of Metaphysic |date=1893 |publisher=Edward Arnold |location=London |url=https://archive.org/details/riddleuniverseb00fawcgoog |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n(1894) ''Swallowed by an Earthquake''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f36qPAAACAAJ|title=Swallowed by an Earthquake|last=Fawcett|first=Edward Douglas|publisher=Edward Around|year=1894|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> a [[subterranean fiction]] adventure about the discovery of an underground world of dinosaurs and cannibals.\n\n(1895) ''The Secret Life of the Desert'' an adventure novel following the exploits of archaeologist Arthur Mannors in Arabia.\n\n(1909) ''The Individual and Reality: An Essay Touching the First Principles of Metaphysics''<ref name=\"Individual\">{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Edward Douglass |title=The Individual and Reality: An Essay Touching the First Principles of Metaphysics |date=1909 |publisher=Longmans, Green, and Co. |url=https://archive.org/details/individualandre00fawcgoog |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n(1916) ''The World as Imagination''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Edward Douglas |title=The World as Imagination |date=1916 |publisher=MacMillan and Co, Ltd |location=London |url=https://archive.org/details/worldasimaginat00fawcgoog|quote=edward fawcett. }}</ref>\n\n(1921) ''Divine Imagining: An Essay on the First Principles of Philosophy''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Divine_Imagining.html?id=2WSToAEACAAJ&source=kp_cover|title=Divine Imagining: An Essay on the First Principles of Philosophy|last=Fawcett|first=Edward Douglass|publisher=|year=1921|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n(1936) ''From Heston to the High Alps: A Chat About Joy-Flying''\n<ref>{{cite web |title=From Heston to the High Alps: A Chat About Joy-Flying|url=https://stellabooks.com/books/douglas-fawcett/from-heston-to-the-high-alps-a-chat-about-joy-flying/1812969 |website=Stella & Rose's Books: Specialists in Rare & Collectable Books |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://theosophy.wiki/en/Edward_Douglas_Fawcett Edward Douglas Fawcett] on Theosophy Wiki\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120403012650/http://www.keverelchess.com/e-douglas-fawcett-1866-1960/ E. Douglas Fawcett (1866\u20131960)] on Keverel Chess\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fawcett, Edward Douglas}}\n[[Category:English Buddhists]]\n[[Category:English Theosophists]]\n[[Category:English science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English mountain climbers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hove]]\n[[Category:English philosophers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n", "name_user": "Klbrain", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:thethe to the", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Douglas_Fawcett"}
